The Twilio Model Context Protocol (MCP) server allows AI agents to interact directly with Twilio’s APIs and documentation within an IDE [1][2]. There are two primary ways to use it depending on your needs.

For documentation and public API discovery, use the hosted, read-only server at `https://mcp.twilio.com/docs` [1]. This requires no authentication and no installation; simply point your MCP-compatible IDE or agent to that URL [1]. It provides two tools: `twiliosearch` to find API operations or documentation, and `twilioretrieve` to fetch parameter schemas [1].

For executing API actions against your Twilio account, use the `@twilio-alpha/mcp` package [3][4]. Because Twilio has thousands of APIs, you must filter tools using `--services` and `--tags` parameters to stay within LLM context limits [4][5][6]. Configure it in your `claude_desktop_config.json` as shown below [4][6]:

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "twilio": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": [
        "-y",
        "@twilio-alpha/mcp",
        "YOUR_ACCOUNT_SID/YOUR_API_KEY:YOUR_API_SECRET",
        "--services", "twilio_api_v2010",
        "--tags", "Api20100401IncomingPhoneNumber"
      ]
    }
  }
}
```
